There was no increased risk of behavioural problems in 210 children whose mothers were treated with SSRI depression compared to 231 children who were more predisposed to behavioral problems such as hyperactivity, lack of attention and socialization.
The same group of Australian researchers also found in a separate study that mothers are more predisposed to blood after birth if treated with SSRI.
Analysis of medical data from 30 198 who were born at a university hospital in Adelaide between 2002 and 2008 showed that the risk of postnatal bleeding increased by 5%, between 11-16%, if women were treated with SSRI.
The risk of severe bleeding or postnatal anaemia has doubled, researchers reported.
Researchers said that although the study has linked the administration of SSRI with increased risk, there are a large number of variables - from medications taken during birth to the limited amount of information received by researchers on the specific medical conditions of women - that could have had an effect on the potential for bleeding.
"It is possible that women who have taken antidepressants at an advanced stage of pregnancy have been those with the most severe stage of the disease, and this is the reason for the increased risk of postnatal, non-antidepressive bleeding," says Dr. Luke Grzeskowiak, professor at Adelaide University.
